This paper is about detecting Android malware using deep learning, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper specifically focuses on using stateful input generation for dynamic analysis, which involves generating inputs that maintain the state of the application during execution. This approach is related to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) since deep learning is used to classify the applications as benign or malware. The paper also discusses the limitations of traditional machine learning techniques, which suggests that software engineering (cs.SE) may be relevant. Finally, the experiments involve testing the system on real devices, which could be considered a form of system and information theory (cs.SI).
